{
  "lesson_id": "lesson_particle_kara",
  "lesson_title": "The Source and the Cause: Particle から (kara)",
  "lesson_summary": "In this lesson, we explore the particle 'kara', which functions as a logical 'origin' marker—identifying either a starting point in time/space or the causal reason behind an event.",
  "grammar_point": "particle_kara",
  "grammar_explanation": {
    "concept": "The particle 'kara' (から) acts like a 'Source' tag. In a spatial/temporal context, it marks where something begins (From). In a logical context, it marks the reason or cause (Because). Think of it as the 'Input' to a process.",
    "formation": "Noun + から (From [Point/Time]); Verb/Adjective + から (Because [Action/State])",
    "variations": [
      "からに (kara ni): Often emphasizes an immediate causal link (Because... then immediately).",
      "ものから (mono kara): A compound meaning 'although' or 'because', often used to link a feeling to a situation."
    ],
    "common_confusions": [
      "vs より (yori): While both can mean 'from', 'yori' is often more formal or used for comparison, whereas 'kara' focuses strictly on the starting point or reason."
    ]
  },
  "teaching_sequence": [
    {
      "type": "introduction",
      "content": "In previous lessons, we looked at 'he' (へ) and 'yori' (より) to describe movement and direction. Now, we turn to 'kara' (から). If 'he' is the destination, 'kara' is the origin. For a Chinese speaker, think of 'kara' as the character '从' (cóng) when dealing with time, and '由于' (yóuyú) when dealing with logic. It identifies the 'source' of the current situation."
    },
